    <teiHeader>
        <fileDesc>
            <titleStmt>
                <title>Thomas Pennant to George Paton, on plans for Low's MS; requesting written
                    materials and prints</title>
            </titleStmt>
            <publicationStmt>
                <publisher/>
            </publicationStmt>
            <sourceDesc>
                <msDesc>
                    <msIdentifier>
                        <settlement>Edinburgh</settlement>
                        <repository>National Library of Scotland</repository>
                        <idno>ADV. MSS. 29.5.5 (2 vols.) i</idno>
                    </msIdentifier>
                    <msContents>
                        <p>
                            <locus>37-38</locus>
                        </p>
                    </msContents>
                    <additional>
                        <p>Pennant's unusual rendering of the year makes the date of this letter
                            difficult to determine, though an unknown hand on the back of the sheet
                            places it in 1774. The existence of a letter from Pennant to Paton dated the
                                10<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> of January 1773 (which makes reference
                            to subjects discussed in adjacent correspondence), suggests that the
                            current letter has been bound out of order, and was in fact written in
                            1774.</p>
                    </additional>
                </msDesc>
            </sourceDesc>
        </fileDesc>
        <profileDesc>
            <correspDesc>
                <correspAction type="sent">
                    <persName ref="pe0232">Thomas Pennant</persName>
                    <date when="1774-01-09"/>
                    <placeName ref="pldb.xml#pl0001">Downing</placeName>
                </correspAction>
                <correspAction type="received">
                    <persName ref="pe0228">George Paton</persName>
                </correspAction>
            </correspDesc>
        </profileDesc>
    </teiHeader>
    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <opener>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Accept first the best wishes for the season &amp; next my best thanks for y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> letters Dec<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> 20<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 30<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> &amp; Jan.1. It
                    will be great pleasure to hear of more of <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bidb.xml#bi0059">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Aulde’s antient
                            tracts</title>
                    </bibl>. be so good as to send me the rest of <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bidb.xml#bi0109">the Gabions</title>
                    </bibl>; which I will keep till
                    they come in use but that will be long, at present let us stick to our islands.
                        Y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> plan for <persName ref="pe0156">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Low</persName> is excellent he will have great
                    advantages with y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> friend <persName ref="pe0306">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                    Aberdeen</persName>.</p>
                <p>Thanks for y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> list of Prints. <placeName ref="pldb.xml#pl0689">
                        <unclear reason="illegible">Ellenstalker</unclear>
                    </placeName> &amp; <placeName ref="pldb.xml#pl0730">Daersie Castles</placeName> will be acceptable.</p>
                <p>Pray stop <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bidb.xml#bi0076">the magazines</title>
                    </bibl>. favor
                    me with account which I will discharge. I have not leisure to look into the
                    numbers missing: but will next summer.</p>
                <note type="editorial">Pennant's letter to Paton on 14<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>
                    February 1773 makes reference to an 'Edinburgh magazine', probably the
                    Ruddimans' <bibl type="editorial">
                        <title ref="bi0064">
                            <hi rend="italic">Weekly
                                Magazine, or, Edinburgh Amusement</hi>
                        </title>
                    </bibl>.</note>
                <p>I heard from <persName ref="pe0156">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                        Low</persName> this day. his plan for visiting the isles is most judicious:
                    I write to him about it this post.</p>
                <p>Y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> account of <persName ref="pe0305">miss
                        Logie</persName> is very curious: it coincides much with a proof of long
                    abstinence now in <placeName ref="pldb.xml#pl0731">Wales</placeName>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>I am Dear Sir Y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Obed<hi rend="superscript">t</hi> H S.</salute>
                    <signed>
                        <persName ref="pe0232">Tho. Pennant</persName>
                    </signed>.</closer>

                <dateline>
                    <placeName ref="pldb.xml#pl0001">Downing</placeName> Jan. 9<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 177¾ </dateline>
            </div>
            <div>
                <p>29</p>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
